{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636268"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:25:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:25:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17576"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17576"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71365"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10266"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56840"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10077"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23987"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23996"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71365"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary site of fatty acid synthesis in human cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mitochondrial matrix","Endoplasmic reticulum","Cytoplasm","Peroxisomes","Golgi apparatus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFatty acid synthesis occurs in the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecytoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E of cells, specifically in the cytosol. This is in contrast to fatty acid breakdown (beta-oxidation) which occurs primarily in mitochondria. The cytoplasmic location allows access to necessary substrates like NADPH and acetyl-CoA (transported out of mitochondria as citrate).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitochondrial matrix\u003C/strong\u003E - This is where fatty acid breakdown occurs, not synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeroxisomes\u003C/strong\u003E - These organelles are involved in breakdown of very long chain fatty acids but not synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoplasmic reticulum\u003C/strong\u003E - While involved in lipid processing and membrane synthesis, this is not the primary site of fatty acid synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGolgi apparatus\u003C/strong\u003E - This organelle is involved in protein processing and sorting but not fatty acid synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key enzymes of fatty acid synthesis, including acetyl-CoA carboxylase and fatty acid synthase, are located in the cytoplasm where they form a coordinated pathway for building fatty acids from acetyl-CoA precursors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fatty acids are broken down through beta-oxidation in mitochondria to produce acetyl-CoA.","The rate-limiting enzyme in fatty acid synthesis is acetyl-CoA carboxylase, which converts acetyl-CoA to malonyl-CoA.","Fatty acid synthesis occurs in the cytoplasm while breakdown occurs in mitochondria."],"references":["Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. Available from: https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"typ